WEBVTT

1
00:00:12.741 --> 00:00:14.738
This is my great uncle,
这是我的曾伯父，

2
00:00:14.738 --> 00:00:17.756
my father's father's younger brother.
我的父亲的父亲的弟弟

3
00:00:17.756 --> 00:00:19.722
His name was Joe McKenna.
他叫乔·麦肯纳

4
00:00:19.962 --> 00:00:24.909
He was a young husband and a semi-pro basketball player
他是一位年轻的丈夫和一位半职业篮球运动员，

5
00:00:24.909 --> 00:00:28.237
and a fireman in New York City.
还是一位纽约市消防员

6
00:00:29.227 --> 00:00:31.827
Family history says he loved being a fireman,
家族史中说他非常喜爱当一名消防员，

7
00:00:31.827 --> 00:00:35.362
and so in 1938, on one of his days off,
在1938年，放假的一天，

8
00:00:35.362 --> 00:00:38.139
he elected to hang out at the firehouse.
他选择去消防站

9
00:00:38.839 --> 00:00:43.038
To make himself useful that day, he started polishing all the brass,
他想帮忙，于是就开始擦拭所有的黄铜，

10
00:00:43.038 --> 00:00:46.432
the railings on the fire truck, the fittings on the walls,
消防车上的栏杆，墙上的配件，

11
00:00:46.432 --> 00:00:48.777
and one of the fire hose nozzles,
其中的一个消防水管的喷嘴，

12
00:00:48.777 --> 00:00:51.285
a giant, heavy piece of metal,
一块巨大，沉重的金属，

13
00:00:51.285 --> 00:00:54.894
toppled off a shelf and hit him.
从架子上掉了下来，并砸中了他

14
00:00:55.394 --> 00:00:59.202
A few days later, his shoulder started to hurt.
几天之后，他的肩膀开始疼痛

15
00:00:59.202 --> 00:01:02.476
Two days after that, he spiked a fever.
再过了两天，他突发高烧。

16
00:01:02.476 --> 00:01:04.961
The fever climbed and climbed.
高烧不退，并且不断攀升

17
00:01:04.961 --> 00:01:06.911
His wife was taking care of him,
他的妻子一直在照顾他，

18
00:01:06.911 --> 00:01:11.213
but nothing she did made a difference, and when they got the local doctor in,
但是她所做的一切都没有用，当他们请来医生时，

19
00:01:11.213 --> 00:01:13.499
nothing he did mattered either.
也对他无能为力

20
00:01:13.969 --> 00:01:17.280
They flagged down a cab and took him to the hospital.
他们拦下了一辆出租车，把他带到医院

21
00:01:17.731 --> 00:01:21.725
The nurses there recognized right away that he had an infection,
那里的护士马上看出他得了感染，

22
00:01:21.725 --> 00:01:25.881
what at the time they would have called "blood poisoning,"
当时候的人把它叫败血症，

23
00:01:25.881 --> 00:01:27.994
and though they probably didn't say it,
尽管他们没有说什么，

24
00:01:27.994 --> 00:01:29.851
they would have known right away
他们肯定马上就知道

25
00:01:29.851 --> 00:01:33.250
that there was nothing they could do.
他们已经无力医治了

26
00:01:33.590 --> 00:01:36.608
There was nothing they could do because the things we use now
他们什么办法都没有是因为我们现在拥有的

27
00:01:36.608 --> 00:01:39.257
to cure infections didn't exist yet.
治疗感染的药品在那时还没有存在

28
00:01:39.557 --> 00:01:42.993
The first test of penicillin, the first antibiotic,
第一个青霉素，抗生素的测试，

29
00:01:42.993 --> 00:01:45.663
was three years in the future.
三年之后才发生

30
00:01:45.663 --> 00:01:50.367
People who got infections either recovered, if they were lucky,
当时一旦得了感染，能够康复算是幸运的，

31
00:01:50.367 --> 00:01:51.862
or they died.
要不然就没命了

32
00:01:52.142 --> 00:01:54.231
My great uncle was not lucky.
我的曾伯父没有那么幸运

33
00:01:54.231 --> 00:01:57.528
He was in the hospital for a week, shaking with chills,
他在医院待了一个星期，一直打寒颤，

34
00:01:57.528 --> 00:01:59.386
dehydrated and delirious,
脱水，并且神志不清，

35
00:01:59.386 --> 00:02:02.288
sinking into a coma as his organs failed.
他的器官衰退，进入了昏迷状态

36
00:02:02.288 --> 00:02:04.424
His condition grew so desperate
他的状况十分危急，

37
00:02:04.424 --> 00:02:09.054
that the people from his firehouse lined up to give him transfusions
消防站的人排队给他输血，

38
00:02:09.054 --> 00:02:12.917
hoping to dilute the infection surging through his blood.
希望能稀释他血液中的感染

39
00:02:13.317 --> 00:02:16.423
Nothing worked. He died.
一切都没有用，他最终不幸去世了

40
00:02:16.963 --> 00:02:19.525
He was 30 years old.
他年仅30岁

41
00:02:19.935 --> 00:02:21.908
If you look back through history,
如果回顾历史，

42
00:02:21.908 --> 00:02:25.182
most people died the way my great uncle died.
有许多人离世的情况同我曾伯父类似

43
00:02:25.182 --> 00:02:27.852
Most people didn't die of cancer or heart disease,
许多人并不是因为癌症或心脏病去世，

44
00:02:27.852 --> 00:02:31.940
the lifestyle diseases that afflict us in the West today.
不是现在折磨我们的生活习惯病

45
00:02:32.310 --> 00:02:38.045
They didn't die of those diseases because they didn't live long enough to develop them.
他们没有患上那些疾病是因为他们活不到得那些疾病的年龄

46
00:02:38.045 --> 00:02:40.158
They died of injuries --
他们是因身体受伤而死 --

47
00:02:40.158 --> 00:02:42.643
being gored by an ox,
被牛角顶伤，

48
00:02:42.643 --> 00:02:44.547
shot on a battlefield,
在战场上中弹，

49
00:02:44.547 --> 00:02:48.285
crushed in one of the new factories of the Industrial Revolution --
在工业革命的新工厂中粉身碎骨 --

50
00:02:48.285 --> 00:02:51.666
and most of the time from infection,
很多时候，是因为得了感染，

51
00:02:51.666 --> 00:02:55.172
which finished what those injuries began.
因伤势造成的感染

52
00:02:56.312 --> 00:02:59.844
All of that changed when antibiotics arrived.
当抗生素到来时，一切都变了

53
00:03:00.419 --> 00:03:04.018
Suddenly, infections that had been a death sentence
曾经意味着死亡的感染突然

54
00:03:04.018 --> 00:03:07.408
became something you recovered from in days.
变成了几天就能恢复的病

55
00:03:07.408 --> 00:03:10.450
It seemed like a miracle,
它就像奇迹

56
00:03:10.450 --> 00:03:16.774
and ever since, we have been living inside the golden epoch of the miracle drugs.
从此以后，我们就一直生活在特效药的黄金时代中

57
00:03:17.114 --> 00:03:21.061
And now, we are coming to an end of it.
现在，它即将结束了

58
00:03:21.061 --> 00:03:26.123
My great uncle died in the last days of the pre-antibiotic era.
我的曾伯父在前抗生素时代最后的日子中去世的

59
00:03:26.123 --> 00:03:31.277
We stand today on the threshold of the post-antibiotic era,
我们现在已经能看到后抗生素时代的到来

60
00:03:31.277 --> 00:03:35.039
in the earliest days of a time when simple infections
感染会像从前一样致命，

61
00:03:35.039 --> 00:03:39.748
such as the one Joe had will kill people once again.
杀死乔（曾伯父）的致命感染会卷土重来

62
00:03:40.704 --> 00:03:43.835
In fact, they already are.
其实，这些感染已经夺取了很多人的性命了

63
00:03:44.605 --> 00:03:47.438
People are dying of infections again because of a phenomenon
人们再次死于感染因为有一种现象

64
00:03:47.438 --> 00:03:49.781
called antibiotic resistance.
叫做抗生素抗药性

65
00:03:50.201 --> 00:03:51.939
Briefly, it works like this.
简单的来说，它的原理是这样的

66
00:03:51.939 --> 00:03:56.911
Bacteria compete against each other for resources, for food,
细菌为了资源和食物相互竞争，

67
00:03:56.911 --> 00:04:01.578
by manufacturing lethal compounds that they direct against each other.
有的细菌会针对性地制造致命的化合物攻击对方

68
00:04:01.578 --> 00:04:03.923
Other bacteria, to protect themselves,
其它的细菌则用化合物保护自己，

69
00:04:03.923 --> 00:04:07.174
evolve defenses against that chemical attack.
发展防御系统对抗这些化学攻击

70
00:04:07.174 --> 00:04:09.496
When we first made antibiotics,
我们最初发明抗生素时，

71
00:04:09.496 --> 00:04:13.698
we took those compounds into the lab and made our own versions of them,
我们在实验室中创造了我们自己版本的化合物

72
00:04:13.698 --> 00:04:18.156
and bacteria responded to our attack the way they always had.
细菌像往常一样对我们的攻击作出了响应

73
00:04:19.494 --> 00:04:21.718
Here is what happened next:
接下来是这样的：

74
00:04:21.918 --> 00:04:25.308
Penicillin was distributed in 1943,
青霉素是在1943年发布的，

75
00:04:25.308 --> 00:04:30.439
and widespread penicillin resistance arrived by 1945.
而广泛的青霉素耐药性在1945年就到来了

76
00:04:30.439 --> 00:04:33.388
Vancomycin arrived in 1972,
万古霉素出现在1972年，

77
00:04:33.388 --> 00:04:36.488
vancomycin resistance in 1988.
万古霉素耐药性就在1988年

78
00:04:36.848 --> 00:04:38.970
Imipenem in 1985,
亚胺培南于1985年，

79
00:04:38.970 --> 00:04:41.742
and resistance to in 1998.
抗药性在1998年又出现了

80
00:04:42.012 --> 00:04:45.680
Daptomycin, one of the most recent drugs, in 2003,
2003年的达托霉素是最新的药物之一，

81
00:04:45.680 --> 00:04:50.045
and resistance to it just a year later in 2004.
抗药性在2004年就紧跟而至

82
00:04:50.395 --> 00:04:54.155
For 70 years, we played a game of leapfrog --
在这70年中，我们像是在做一个蛙跳的游戏 --

83
00:04:54.155 --> 00:04:57.081
our drug and their resistance,
一种药物，一种抗药性，

84
00:04:57.081 --> 00:05:00.726
and then another drug, and then resistance again --
接下来又一种药物，又一个抗药性 --

85
00:05:00.726 --> 00:05:03.037
and now the game is ending.
现在这个游戏结束了

86
00:05:03.257 --> 00:05:07.297
Bacteria develop resistance so quickly that pharmaceutical companies
细菌的抵抗力极快，以至于制药公司

87
00:05:07.297 --> 00:05:11.662
have decided making antibiotics is not in their best interest,
认为生产抗生素不是他们的最佳利益，

88
00:05:11.662 --> 00:05:14.472
so there are infections moving across the world
所以现在各种感染风靡全球，

89
00:05:14.472 --> 00:05:17.931
for which, out of the more than 100 antibiotics
市场上可购买到的100多种

90
00:05:17.931 --> 00:05:20.160
available on the market,
抗生素中，

91
00:05:20.160 --> 00:05:23.574
two drugs might work with side effects,
可能只有两种药物会管用，并带有副作用

92
00:05:23.574 --> 00:05:26.058
or one drug,
或者一个药，

93
00:05:26.058 --> 00:05:27.466
or none.
甚至没有

94
00:05:27.916 --> 00:05:29.488
This is what that looks like.
看上去就是这个样子的

95
00:05:30.098 --> 00:05:34.278
In 2000, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the CDC,
在2000年，疾病控制与预防中心（CDC），

96
00:05:34.278 --> 00:05:36.321
identified a single case
鉴定有一例患者

97
00:05:36.321 --> 00:05:38.573
in a hospital in North Carolina
在一家位于北卡罗来纳的医院里

98
00:05:38.573 --> 00:05:42.306
of an infection resistant to all but two drugs.
除了两种药外，对其它药物都有抗药性

99
00:05:42.706 --> 00:05:47.025
Today, that infection, known as KPC,
现在，这种感染被称为KPC，

100
00:05:47.025 --> 00:05:49.625
has spread to every state but three,
除了3个州外，已经传播到了美国各地，

101
00:05:49.625 --> 00:05:51.970
and to South America, Europe
还有南美，欧洲

102
00:05:51.970 --> 00:05:54.177
and the Middle East.
和中东地区

103
00:05:54.687 --> 00:05:57.009
In 2008, doctors in Sweden
在2008年，瑞典医生

104
00:05:57.009 --> 00:05:59.795
diagnosed a man from India with a different infection
确诊一名来自印度的男子患有的感染

105
00:05:59.795 --> 00:06:03.510
resistant to all but one drug that time.
只对一种药没有抗药性

106
00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:05.739
The gene that creates that resistance,
创造这种抗药性的基因

107
00:06:05.739 --> 00:06:12.264
known as NDM, has now spread from India into China, Asia, Africa,
叫做NDM，现在已经从印度传播到中国，亚洲，非洲，

108
00:06:12.264 --> 00:06:16.629
Europe and Canada, and the United States.
欧洲和加拿大，还有美国

109
00:06:16.949 --> 00:06:19.508
It would be natural to hope
我们真心希望

110
00:06:19.508 --> 00:06:23.107
that these infections are extraordinary cases,
这些感染病例只是罕见情况，

111
00:06:23.107 --> 00:06:24.965
but in fact,
但是其实，

112
00:06:24.965 --> 00:06:27.426
in the United States and Europe,
在美国和欧洲，

113
00:06:27.426 --> 00:06:30.142
50,000 people a year
每年都有50,000人

114
00:06:30.142 --> 00:06:34.266
die of infections which no drugs can help.
死于无药可救的感染

115
00:06:34.786 --> 00:06:37.828
A project chartered by the British government
一项由英国政府特许的项目

116
00:06:37.828 --> 00:06:41.566
known as the Review on Antimicrobial Resistance
叫做抗生素抗药性评审

117
00:06:41.566 --> 00:06:48.938
estimates that the worldwide toll right now is 700,000 deaths a year.
预计每年全球死亡人数有700,000

118
00:06:50.111 --> 00:06:54.475
That is a lot of deaths,
这个数字巨大，

119
00:06:54.475 --> 00:06:57.587
and yet, the chances are good that you don't feel at risk,
然而这个比例还是很小，所以我们感觉不到风险，

120
00:06:57.587 --> 00:07:00.815
that you imagine these people were hospital patients
你想象他们是医院里的病人

121
00:07:00.815 --> 00:07:02.533
in intensive care units
在重症监护室

122
00:07:02.533 --> 00:07:06.480
or nursing home residents near the ends of their lives,
或者住在疗养院中，接近生命的尽头，

123
00:07:06.480 --> 00:07:09.661
people whose infections are remote from us,
感觉他们离我们很远，

124
00:07:09.661 --> 00:07:12.865
in situations we can't identify with.
他们的状况我们还很陌生

125
00:07:14.275 --> 00:07:17.672
What you didn't think about, none of us do,
你们想不到的是，我们所有人都想不到的是

126
00:07:17.672 --> 00:07:22.638
is that antibiotics support almost all of modern life.
抗生素支撑着几乎所有的现代生活

127
00:07:23.541 --> 00:07:25.752
If we lost antibiotics,
如果我们失去了抗生素，

128
00:07:25.752 --> 00:07:27.206
here's what else we'd lose:
我们还会失去所有这些东西：

129
00:07:27.656 --> 00:07:31.835
First, any protection for people with weakened immune systems --
首先，所有免疫系统较弱的人都失去了保护 --

130
00:07:31.835 --> 00:07:35.295
cancer patients, AIDS patients,
癌症患者，艾滋病患者，

131
00:07:35.295 --> 00:07:39.799
transplant recipients, premature babies.
器官移植接受者，早产婴儿

132
00:07:39.799 --> 00:07:44.211
Next, any treatment that installs foreign objects in the body:
接下来，任何需要在人体中安装异物的治疗：

133
00:07:44.211 --> 00:07:48.089
stents for stroke, pumps for diabetes,
中风时使用的支架，治疗糖尿病的胰岛素磊

134
00:07:48.089 --> 00:07:52.013
dialysis, joint replacements.
透析，关节置换

135
00:07:52.013 --> 00:07:55.728
How many athletic baby boomers need new hips and knees?
婴儿潮一代的运动员有多少需要髋关节，膝关节置换？

136
00:07:55.728 --> 00:07:58.537
A recent study estimates that without antibiotics,
一个近期的研究预计如果没有抗生素，

137
00:07:58.537 --> 00:08:02.054
one out of ever six would die.
每六个人中就会有一人死亡

138
00:08:02.484 --> 00:08:05.689
Next, we'd probably lose surgery.
接下来，我们可能会失去手术

139
00:08:05.689 --> 00:08:08.011
Many operations are preceded
很多手术的进行

140
00:08:08.011 --> 00:08:10.959
by prophylactic doses of antibiotics.
需要预防性剂量的抗生素

141
00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:12.631
Without that protection,
如果没有这个措施，

142
00:08:12.631 --> 00:08:16.835
we'd lose the ability to open the hidden spaces of the body.
我们就不可能对人体隐蔽的器官开刀

143
00:08:16.835 --> 00:08:19.668
So no heart operations,
于是就不会有心脏手术，

144
00:08:19.668 --> 00:08:22.500
no prostate biopsies,
没有前列腺活检，

145
00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:25.202
no Cesarean sections.
没有剖腹产

146
00:08:25.612 --> 00:08:30.264
We'd have to learn to fear infections that now seem minor.
我们会惧怕那些现在看似微小的感染

147
00:08:30.604 --> 00:08:34.412
Strep throat used to cause heart failure.
咽喉炎以前会导致心脏衰竭

148
00:08:34.412 --> 00:08:37.059
Skin infections led to amputations.
皮肤感染会发展成截肢

149
00:08:37.639 --> 00:08:40.542
Giving birth killed, in the cleanest hospitals,
即使在最干净的医院，孕产妇的死亡率

150
00:08:40.542 --> 00:08:43.217
almost one woman out of every 100.
几乎达到百分之一

151
00:08:43.537 --> 00:08:48.370
Pneumonia took three children out of every 10.
每10个孩子中，肺炎会夺走3个孩子的生命

152
00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:51.153
More than anything else,
更重要的是，

153
00:08:51.153 --> 00:08:55.528
we'd lose the confident way we live our everyday lives.
我们失去了生活的信心

154
00:08:56.656 --> 00:09:00.863
If you knew that any injury could kill you,
如果你知道任何伤口都有可能致命，

155
00:09:00.863 --> 00:09:04.109
would you ride a motorcycle,
你还会不会去骑摩托车，

156
00:09:04.109 --> 00:09:07.320
bomb down a ski slope,
从雪山上飞驰而下，

157
00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:10.796
climb a ladder to hang your Christmas lights,
爬上梯子去挂你的圣诞彩灯，

158
00:09:10.796 --> 00:09:14.463
let your kid slide into home plate?
让你的孩子滑进本垒吗？

159
00:09:15.393 --> 00:09:18.458
After all, the first person to receive penicillin,
毕竟，第一名接受青霉素的病人，

160
00:09:18.458 --> 00:09:22.336
a British policeman named Albert Alexander,
一名叫阿尔伯特·亚历山大英国警察，

161
00:09:22.336 --> 00:09:26.678
who was so ravaged by infection that his scalp oozed pus
他的感染严重到他的头皮都渗出了脓液，

162
00:09:26.678 --> 00:09:29.603
and doctors had to take out an eye,
一只眼睛也被医生摘除了，

163
00:09:29.603 --> 00:09:32.982
was infected by doing something very simple.
他的感染的起因十分微不足道

164
00:09:33.992 --> 00:09:38.808
He walked into his garden and scratched his face on a thorn.
他走进他的花园，然后脸上被刺划伤了

165
00:09:40.651 --> 00:09:48.178
That British project I mentioned which estimates that the worldwide toll right now is 700,000 deaths a year
刚才我提到的英国项目预计现在每年的全球死亡人数为700,000人

166
00:09:48.178 --> 00:09:54.355
also predicts that if we can't get this under control by 2050,
他们也预测如果我们无法在2050年前控制现在的情况，

167
00:09:54.355 --> 00:10:01.947
not long, the worldwide toll will be 10 million deaths a year.
在不久的将来，全球死亡人数会上升到一千万

168
00:10:01.947 --> 00:10:04.649
How did we get to this point
我们是如何走到这一步的，

169
00:10:04.649 --> 00:10:06.684
where what we have to look forward to
面对这些可怕的数字

170
00:10:06.684 --> 00:10:10.167
is those terrifying numbers?
我们的未来将何去何从？

171
00:10:10.167 --> 00:10:14.355
The difficult answer is, we did it to ourselves.
残酷的现实是，这都是我们的所作所为

172
00:10:14.695 --> 00:10:17.667
Resistance is an inevitable biological process,
抗药性是一个必然的生物过程，

173
00:10:17.667 --> 00:10:21.720
but we bear the responsibility for accelerating it.
但是我们要为加快这一过程承担责任

174
00:10:22.310 --> 00:10:25.863
We did this by squandering antibiotics
我们随心所欲地滥用抗生素的行为

175
00:10:25.863 --> 00:10:29.951
with a heedlessness that now seems shocking.
现在看来十分触目惊心

176
00:10:31.228 --> 00:10:35.314
Penicillin was sold over the counter until the 1950s.
青霉素在上世纪50年代之前是非处方药

177
00:10:35.314 --> 00:10:38.649
In much of the developing world, most antibiotics still are.
在很多发展中国家，很多抗生素依旧是

178
00:10:39.029 --> 00:10:46.483
In the United States, 50 percent of the antibiotics given in hospitals are unnecessary.
在美国，医院给出的50%的抗生素都是没有必要的

179
00:10:46.483 --> 00:10:50.857
Forty-five percent of the prescriptions written in doctor's offices
医生办公室中开出的45%的药

180
00:10:50.857 --> 00:10:54.830
are for conditions that antibiotics cannot help.
都是抗生素治不了的病

181
00:10:56.397 --> 00:10:59.067
And that's just in healthcare.
这只是在医疗系统中的数据

182
00:10:59.067 --> 00:11:03.920
On much of the planet, most meat animals get antibiotics every day of their lives,
在全球很多地方，许多家畜每天都进食抗生素，

183
00:11:03.920 --> 00:11:06.196
not to cure illnesses,
不是为了治疗疾病，

184
00:11:06.196 --> 00:11:09.655
but to fatten them up and to protect them against
而是把它们催肥，为了在

185
00:11:09.655 --> 00:11:13.626
the factory farm conditions they are raised in.
工厂化养殖的环境下保护它们

186
00:11:13.626 --> 00:11:16.644
In the United States, possibly 80 percent
在美国，每年大约有80%的

187
00:11:16.644 --> 00:11:23.347
of the antibiotics sold every year go to farm animals, not to humans,
抗生素是卖给农场动物的，不是病人，

188
00:11:23.347 --> 00:11:29.647
creating resistant bacteria that move off the farm in water, in dust,
于是创造了抗药性细菌，它们从农场流到了水里，到灰尘中，

189
00:11:29.647 --> 00:11:32.515
in the meat the animals become.
到这些动物最终变成的肉制品中

190
00:11:32.805 --> 00:11:35.730
Aquaculture depends on antibiotics too,
水产养殖也依赖抗生素，

191
00:11:35.730 --> 00:11:37.379
particularly in Asia,
尤其是在亚洲，

192
00:11:37.379 --> 00:11:40.722
and fruit growing relies on antibiotics
水果种植也依靠抗生素，

193
00:11:40.722 --> 00:11:45.621
to protect apples, pears, citrus, against disease.
让苹果，梨，柑橘远离病害，

194
00:11:46.311 --> 00:11:51.937
And because bacteria can pass their DNA to each other
由于细菌能够互相传递DNA

195
00:11:51.937 --> 00:11:56.372
like a traveler handing off a suitcase at an airport,
就像一个旅客在机场托运行李，

196
00:11:56.372 --> 00:12:01.180
once we have encouraged that resistance into existence,
一旦我们促进这种耐药性，

197
00:12:01.180 --> 00:12:03.407
there is no knowing where it will spread.
就无法控制它的传播

198
00:12:05.543 --> 00:12:07.114
This was predictable.
这是可预测的

199
00:12:07.494 --> 00:12:10.326
In fact, it was predicted
事实上，发现青霉素的科学家，

200
00:12:10.326 --> 00:12:14.761
by Alexander Fleming, the man who discovered penicillin.
亚历山大·弗莱明早已预测到了

201
00:12:14.761 --> 00:12:18.755
He was given the Nobel Prize in 1945 in recognition,
他在1945年获得诺贝尔奖表彰，

202
00:12:18.755 --> 00:12:23.102
and in an interview shortly after, this is what he said:
在之后的一个采访中，他说：

203
00:12:23.102 --> 00:12:27.369
"The thoughtless person playing with penicillin treatment
“滥用青霉素的无知的人

204
00:12:27.369 --> 00:12:30.643
is morally responsible for the death of a man
将在道德上为他人的死负责，

205
00:12:30.643 --> 00:12:32.967
who succumbs to infection
他的无知带来了耐药性的问题，

206
00:12:32.967 --> 00:12:35.870
with a pencillin-resistant organism."
导致那些人为此丧命。“

207
00:12:35.870 --> 00:12:40.155
He added, "I hope this evil can be averted."
他补充道：”我希望能够避免这个厄运。“

208
00:12:40.806 --> 00:12:43.662
Can we avert it?
我们能避免它吗？

209
00:12:43.662 --> 00:12:47.330
There are companies working on novel antibiotics,
有些公司正在研发新型抗生素，

210
00:12:47.330 --> 00:12:50.906
things the superbugs have never seen before.
一些超级细菌从未见过的东西

211
00:12:50.906 --> 00:12:53.623
We need those new drugs badly,
我们十分迫切地需要这些药物，

212
00:12:53.623 --> 00:12:55.875
and we need incentives:
我们也需要一些奖励：

213
00:12:55.875 --> 00:12:58.406
discovery grants, extended patents,
研发补助，延长专利，

214
00:12:58.406 --> 00:13:05.163
prizes, to lure other companies into making antibiotics again.
奖金等等，去吸引其它公司再次制造去抗生素

215
00:13:05.163 --> 00:13:07.529
But that probably won't be enough.
但是这还不够

216
00:13:07.879 --> 00:13:11.983
Here's why: Evolution always wins.
这就是原因：大自然的进化总会赢

217
00:13:12.523 --> 00:13:16.447
Bacteria birth a new generation every 20 minutes.
细菌每20分钟就能生成新的一代

218
00:13:16.447 --> 00:13:21.230
It takes pharmaceutical chemistry 10 years to derive a new drug.
药物化学家需要花10年才能制成一种新的药

219
00:13:21.230 --> 00:13:24.086
Every time we use an antibiotic,
每次我们使用一种新的抗生素时，

220
00:13:24.086 --> 00:13:27.360
we give the bacteria billions of chances
我们就给了细菌数亿次机会

221
00:13:27.360 --> 00:13:32.306
to crack the codes of the defenses we've constructed.
去破解我们建造的防御系统的密码

222
00:13:32.306 --> 00:13:37.251
There has never yet been a drug they could not defeat.
迄今为止，任何药物都不能够打败它们

223
00:13:37.251 --> 00:13:40.781
This is asymmetric warfare,
这是一场不公平的战争，

224
00:13:40.781 --> 00:13:44.789
but we can change the outcome.
但是我们能够改变它的结果

225
00:13:45.749 --> 00:13:52.154
We could build systems to harvest data to tell us automatically and specifically
我们能够创造一个系统去收集数据，并且自动、具体地

226
00:13:52.154 --> 00:13:55.083
how antibiotics are being used.
告诉我们抗生素是如何被使用的

227
00:13:55.083 --> 00:13:57.916
We could build gatekeeping into drug order systems
我们可以在药物订购系统中放置守门人，

228
00:13:57.916 --> 00:14:01.631
so that every prescription gets a second look.
再次检查每一个处方

229
00:14:01.631 --> 00:14:07.740
We could require agriculture to give up antibiotic use.
我们可以要求在农业中不再使用抗生素

230
00:14:08.063 --> 00:14:11.095
We could build surveillance systems
我们可以构建监控系统

231
00:14:11.095 --> 00:14:15.321
to tell us where resistance is emerging next.
及时告知我们哪里出现了抗药性

232
00:14:15.321 --> 00:14:17.634
Those are the tech solutions.
这些是科技解决方案

233
00:14:18.084 --> 00:14:20.708
They probably aren't enough either,
这些还不够，

234
00:14:20.708 --> 00:14:23.937
unless we help.
我们都要出一份力

235
00:14:27.605 --> 00:14:29.919
Antibiotic resistance is a habit.
抗生素耐药性是一种习惯

236
00:14:30.299 --> 00:14:33.387
We all know how hard it is to change a habit.
我们都知道改掉一种习惯是很难的

237
00:14:33.387 --> 00:14:37.917
But as a society, we've done that in the past.
但是作为社会中的一员，我们曾经做到过

238
00:14:38.217 --> 00:14:41.792
People used to toss litter into the streets,
人们曾经在马路上随便扔垃圾，

239
00:14:41.792 --> 00:14:43.557
used to not wear seatbelts,
曾经不系安全带，

240
00:14:43.557 --> 00:14:47.814
used to smoke inside public buildings.
曾经在公共场所抽烟

241
00:14:48.224 --> 00:14:50.444
We don't do those things anymore.
我们不再这么做了

242
00:14:50.964 --> 00:14:53.286
We don't trash the environment
我们不破坏环境，

243
00:14:53.286 --> 00:14:56.443
or court devastating accidents
不引发巨大事故，

244
00:14:56.443 --> 00:14:59.415
or expose others to the possibility of cancer,
不再使别人得到患有癌症的风险，

245
00:14:59.415 --> 00:15:02.922
because we decided those things were expensive,
因为我们懂得那些事情代价太高，

246
00:15:02.922 --> 00:15:06.995
destructive, not in our best interest.
具有毁灭性，对我们没有一点益处

247
00:15:07.635 --> 00:15:10.535
We changed social norms.
我们改变了社会规范

248
00:15:10.955 --> 00:15:15.099
We could change social norms around antibiotic use too.
我们也可以改变抗生素使用的规范

249
00:15:17.319 --> 00:15:21.498
I know that the scale of antibiotic resistance seems overwhelming,
我知道抗生素耐药性的规模看似巨大，

250
00:15:21.498 --> 00:15:24.958
but if you've ever bought a fluorescent lightbulb
但是如果你对气候变化感到忧虑，

251
00:15:24.958 --> 00:15:27.674
because you were concerned about climate change,
于是去购买荧光灯泡，

252
00:15:27.674 --> 00:15:30.809
or read the label on a box of crackers
或者考虑到棕榈油毁林，

253
00:15:30.809 --> 00:15:35.290
because you think about the deforestation from palm oil,
就每次阅读一盒饼干上的标签

254
00:15:35.290 --> 00:15:38.169
you already know what it feels like
你应该已经知道

255
00:15:38.169 --> 00:15:43.169
to take a tiny step to address an overwhelming problem.
用生活中的一点一滴去改变一个大问题是什么样的感觉

256
00:15:43.649 --> 00:15:48.130
We could take those kinds of steps for antibiotic use too.
我们也可以用这样的方式去改变抗生素的使用

257
00:15:48.130 --> 00:15:55.767
We could forgo giving an antibiotic if we're not sure it's the right one.
如果不确定我们是否正确使用抗生素，那就放弃它

258
00:15:56.071 --> 00:16:02.384
We could stop insisting on a prescription for our kid's ear infection
我们可以不要执意为孩子的耳部感染开处方，

259
00:16:02.384 --> 00:16:04.282
before we're sure what caused it.
而是先查明起因

260
00:16:05.498 --> 00:16:08.865
We could ask every restaurant,
我们可以询问每一家餐厅，

261
00:16:08.865 --> 00:16:10.676
every supermarket,
每一家超市

262
00:16:10.676 --> 00:16:12.296
where their meat comes from.
它们的肉制品是从哪里来的

263
00:16:12.626 --> 00:16:14.460
We could promise each other
我们可以做承诺

264
00:16:14.460 --> 00:16:21.449
never again to buy chicken or shrimp or fruit raised with routine antibiotic use,
不再购买长期使用抗生素养殖的鸡，虾或水果，

265
00:16:21.449 --> 00:16:24.143
and if we did those things,
若果我们能做到这些，

266
00:16:24.143 --> 00:16:28.635
we could slow down the arrival of the post-antibiotic world.
我们可以减缓后抗生素时代的到来

267
00:16:29.367 --> 00:16:33.500
But we have to do it soon.
但是我们要马上开始行动

268
00:16:33.500 --> 00:16:38.005
Penicillin began the antibiotic era in 1943.
青霉素在1943年开启了抗生素时代

269
00:16:38.005 --> 00:16:43.711
In just 70 years, we walked ourselves up to the edge of disaster.
仅仅70年后，我们已经走在灾难的边缘

270
00:16:44.111 --> 00:16:46.433
We won't get 70 years
我们没有70年的时间

271
00:16:46.433 --> 00:16:50.159
to find our way back out again.
去找到我们的出路

272
00:16:50.589 --> 00:16:52.099
Thank you very much.
谢谢大家！

273
00:16:52.609 --> 00:16:58.460
(Applause)
（掌声）